Strings are compared lexicographically, according to the Unicode order of each character. Since numerals `0` to `9` are all earlier in Unicode order than capital letters `F` and `B`, then it follows that e.g. `&#39;18&#39; &gt; &#39;Fizz&#39;` is `False`. However, the empty string comes first, by definition of lexicographical ordering; so `&#39;19&#39; &gt; &#39;&#39;` is `True`. So whenever we have a `&#39;Fizz&#39;`, a `&#39;Buzz&#39;` or a `&#39;FizzBuzz&#39;`, that&#39;s the string that `max` picks; if we don&#39;t, and have an empty string, then we get `str(i)` out of `max`.

    int(True)
    # =&gt; 1
    int(False)
    # =&gt; 0
    18 % 3 == 0
    # =&gt; True
    19 % 3 == 0
    # =&gt; False
    &#39;&#39; + 1 * &#39;Fizz&#39; + 1 * &#39;Buzz&#39;
    # =&gt; &#39;FizzBuzz&#39;
    &#39;&#39; + 0 * &#39;Fizz&#39; + 0 * &#39;Buzz&#39;
    # =&gt; &#39;&#39;

How do we even get a `&#39;Fizz&#39;`, a `&#39;Buzz&#39;` or a `&#39;FizzBuzz&#39;` in the first place? `i % 3 == 0` is `True` for numbers cleanly divisible by 3. `True` in Python, if coerced to a number, is `1`. `&#39;Fizz&#39; * 1` gives one repetition of `&#39;Fizz&#39;` (`&#39;Fizz&#39; * 3` would produce `FizzFizzFizz`). On the other hand, for numbers not cleanly divisible by 3, `False` is coerced to `0`; and zero times `&#39;Fizz&#39;` is an empty string. If we have a number that is cleanly divisible by both `3` and `5`, we get `&#39;&#39; + &#39;Fizz&#39; + &#39;Buzz&#39;` for the string.

TypesScript provides [namespace][1] [merging][2] in order to enable code splitting across multiple files. 

The following code will merge `BookingInquiry` as member into `Bookings` namespace. Pay attention to the position of `export namespace BookinInquiry`: it&#39;s inside the namespace and not at the top-level, so the file belongs to the global namespace. `export` inside the namespace has nothing to do with module imports: it makes the member public to namespace consumers.
```
/* BookingInquiry.ts */
namespace Bookings {
  export namespace BookingInquiry {
    export interface FormState {
      date?: Date;
      organizer?: Partial&lt;Contact&gt;;
      location?: Partial&lt;Location&gt;;
    }
  }
}
```
Bookings namespace will drop the `BookingInquiry` member and get leaner. 
```
/* Bookings.ts */
namespace Bookings {
  // example: Bookings.Status.Complete
  export enum Status {
    Initialized,
    Created,
    Complete,
    Cancelled
  }
  // more code...
}
```

Unfortunately, you cannot keep your namespace structure only in `Bookings.ts` - you will also have to re-declare `Bookings` as parent namespace of `BookingInquiry`. That is, because namespaces are considered named [JavaScript object in the *global namespace*][3] to be consumed via `&lt;script&gt;` and are resolved to `var`. You cannot `import` code from a module into namespaces: if you write `export namespace BookingInquiry` at the top level of a file, TypeScript will treat that file as *module* which you cannot import in `Bookings.ts` namespace. There is no special `import` declaration to import other namespaces, so the parent-child relation has to be made explicit in `BookingInquiry.ts`.

Having said that, I don&#39;t really understand why you export your namespaces in the top level, as they are considered to be contained in modules then and create [needless namespacing][4]. You&#39;ll want to use namespaces for global scripts OR use module resolution, where the latter is the [recommended approach][5] in most cases:

&gt; Modules provide for better code reuse, stronger isolation and better tooling support for bundling. [...] Starting with ECMAScript 2015, modules are native part of the language, and should be  supported by all compliant engine implementations. Thus, for new projects modules would be the recommended code organization mechanism.

So you can drop the top-level `export` like in the code example (global namespaces) or use modules entirely. PS: If you want to make your namespace leaner by outsourcing types, you can make use of [import types][6].
```
// my-type.d.ts
export type MyType = {
  foo: string;
  bar: number;
};

// Bookings.ts
namespace Bookings {
 export const foo: import(&quot;./my-types&quot;).MyType = { foo: &quot;lala&quot;, bar: 42 };
}
```

Hope, it helps!

  [1]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/namespaces.html#splitting-across-files
  [2]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/declaration-merging.html#merging-namespaces
  [3]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/namespaces-and-modules.html#using-namespaces
  [4]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/namespaces-and-modules.html#needless-namespacing
  [5]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/namespaces-and-modules.html
  [6]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-2-9.html#import-types

